71.8	One_Hundred_Years_of_Solitude	One Hundred Years of Solitude	One Hundred Years of Solitude (Spanish: , 1967), by Gabriel García Márquez, is a novel that tells the multi-generational story of the Buendía family, whose patriarch, José Arcadio Buendía, founds the town of Macondo, the metaphoric Colombia. The non-linear story is narrated via different time frames, a technique derived from the Argentine writer Jorge Luis Borges (as in The Garden of Forking Paths).	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/9d/100years.jpg/200px-100years.jpg
